\f + \fr 7:2\ft With common hands. It may be translated, with defiled hands; as also ver. 15; but the circumstances plainly shew the sense. (Witham)\f*
\f + \fr 7:3\ft Often washing, etc.{ Ver. 3. Crebò, ean me pugme. Mr. Bois, prebend of Ely, defends the Latin version, and says pugme comes from pukna and puknos. But Theophylactus would have it to signify, up to the elbows; achri tou agkonos.|} Some would have the Greek to signify unless they wash up to the elbows, but I think without sufficient grounds. (Witham)\f*
\f + \fr 7:4\ft Washed: literally, baptized. By beds are not understood night beds, but couches to eat upon, as it was then the custom. (Witham)\f*
\f + \fr 7:7\ft See the annotations Matthew 15:9, 11. It is groundless to pretend from this text, that the precepts and traditions of the Church are not binding and obligatory, for Christ himself has commanded all to hear his Church, and obey their lawful pastors. These indeed may be called the precepts of men, but they are precepts of men invested with power and authority from God, and of whom Christ himself said, (Luke 10:16.) He that heareth you, heareth me; and he that despiseth you, despiseth me.\f*
\f + \fr 7:9\ft Well do you. Christ here speaks by the figure called irony. (Witham)\f*
\f + \fr 7:17\ft Asked him the parable. Asked him to explain its meaning.\f*
\f + \fr 7:24\ft If he desired to conceal himself, and could not, his will it seems was under control; but this is impossible. His will must always take place. On this occasion, therefore, he wished himself to be sought for by these Gentiles, but not to be made known by his own apostles. Wherefore it came to pass, that not the persons who were his followers, but the Gentiles who entered the house in which he was, published his fame abroad. (St. Augustine) --- Jesus Christ commanded his disciples not to publish that he was come into that country; not that he intended to cease from healing the infirm, and curing diseases, when he saw the faith of the inhabitants deserved it; for he informed the Gentile woman of his coming, and made it known to as many others as he thought worthy; but that he might teach us, by his example, to decline the applause of men. (Ven. Bede)\f*
\f + \fr 7:25\ft This part, in which St. Mark says that Christ was in the house, when the woman came to petition in behalf of her daughter, seems to differ from the narration of St. Matthew, who says that the disciples besought Christ to dismiss her, because she cried after them; by which he signifies, that she followed them as they were on the road. These apparent differences may thus easily be reconciled. The woman came to our Lord when he was in the house, and he, according to St. Matthew, not answering her a word, went out during the silence: the woman followed after, and by her perseverance obtained her request. (St. Augustine)\f*
\f + \fr 7:32\ft Dumb.{ Ver. 32. Mutum, dumb; Greek, mogilalon, qui parum loquitur.|} The Greek signifies one that speaks little, or with difficulty. (Witham) --- They besought him. In the Greek it is, they beseech him, which agrees so well with they bring, that we have every reason to believe that this was the original reading.\f*
\f + \fr 7:34\ft Ephphetha, a Syriac word. Jesus Christ, in the cure of this man, uses many and various actions; but as of their own nature they are no ways equal to such a cure, they shew: first, that the cure was miraculous; and secondly, the virtue, which his divinity communicated to his sacred body. (Bible de Vence) --- We must not suppose that our Saviour here groaned on account of any difficulty he experienced in working this miracle, but only from commiseration for the man, whom he was about to heal; as likewise to shew, how very difficult is the cure of those who are spiritually deaf and dumb by sin. He was affected in a similar manner when he raised Lazarus to life, to shew with what difficulty a man, dead and buried in sin by evil habits, can arise from that miserable state. (Denis the Carthusian)\f*
<>
\c 8
\cl Mark 8
\cd Christ feeds four thousand. He gives sight to a blind man. He foretells his passion.
\p
\v 1 In *those days again, when there was a great multitude, and they had nothing to eat; calling his disciples together, he saith to them:
\p
\v 2 I have compassion on the multitude: for behold they have now been with me three days, and have nothing to eat:
\p
\v 3 And if I shall send them away fasting to their own houses, they will faint in the way; for some of them came from afar off.
\p
\v 4 And his disciples answered him: From whence can any one satisfy them here with bread in the wilderness?
\p
\v 5 And he asked them: How many loaves have ye? and they said: Seven.
\p
\v 6 And he commanded the people to sit down on the ground: and taking the seven loaves, giving thanks, he broke, and gave to his disciples to set before them, and they set them before the people.
\p
\v 7 And they had a few little fishes: and he blessed them, and commanded them to be set before them.
\p
\v 8 And they did eat and were filled, and they took up that which was left of the fragments, seven baskets.
\p
\v 9 And they that had eaten were about four thousand: and he sent them away.
\p
\v 10 And immediately going up into a ship with his disciples, he came into the parts of Dalmanutha.
\p
\v 11 *And the Pharisees came forth, and began to question with him, seeking of him a sign from heaven, tempting him.
\p
\v 12 And sighing deeply in spirit, he saith: Why doth this generation seek a sign? Amen, I say to you, a sign shall not be given to this generation.
\p
\v 13 And leaving them, he went up again into the ship, and passed to the other side of the water.
\p
\v 14 And they forgot to take bread: and they had but one loaf with them in the ship.
\p
\v 15 And he charged them, saying: Take heed and beware of the leaven of the Pharisees, and of the leaven of Herod.
\p
\v 16 And they reasoned among themselves, saying: Because we have no bread.
\p
\v 17 Which Jesus knowing, saith to them: Why do you reason, because you have no bread? do you not yet know nor understand? have you still your heart blinded?
\p
\v 18 Having eyes, see you not? and having ears, hear you not? *Neither do you remember.
\p
\v 19 When I broke the five loaves among five thousand: how many baskets full of fragments took you up? They say to him: Twelve.
\p
\v 20 And when the seven loaves among four thousand, how many baskets of fragments took you up? And they say to him: Seven.
\p
\v 21 And he said to them: How do you not yet understand?
\p
\v 22 And they came to Bethsaida: and they bring to him a blind man, and they besought him to touch him.
\p
\v 23 And taking the blind man by the hand, he led him out of the town: and spitting upon his eyes, laying his hands on him, he asked him if he saw any thing.
\p
\v 24 And looking up, he said: I see men, as trees, walking.
\p
\v 25 After that he laid his hands again upon his eyes, and he began to see, and was restored, so that he saw all things clearly.
\p
\v 26 And he sent him to his house; saying: Go into thy house, and if thou enter into the town, tell nobody.
\p
\v 27 *And Jesus went out, and his disciples, into the towns of Caesarea Philippi; and in the way he asked his disciples, saying to them: **Whom do men say that I am?
\p
\v 28 And they answered him, saying: John the Baptist; but some Elias, and others as one of the prophets.
\p
\v 29 Then he saith to them: But whom do you say that I am? Peter answering, said to him: Thou art the Christ.
\p
\v 30 And he strictly charged them that they should not tell any man of him.
\p
\v 31 And he began to teach them, that the Son of man must suffer many things, and be rejected by the ancients, and by the high priests, and the Scribes, and be killed: and after three days rise again.
\p
\v 32 And he spoke the word openly: *And Peter taking him, began to rebuke him.
\p
\v 33 But he turning about and seeing his disciples, threatened Peter, saying: Go after me, Satan, because thou dost not relish the things that are of God, but the things that are of men.
\p
\v 34 And calling together the multitude with his disciples, he said to them: *If any man will follow me, let him deny himself, and take up his cross, and follow me.
\p
\v 35 *For whosoever will save his life, shall lose it; and whosoever shall lose his life for my sake, and for the gospel, shall save it.
\p
\v 36 For what shall it profit a man, if he gain the whole world, and lose his own soul?
\p
\v 37 Or what shall a man give in exchange for his soul?
\p
\v 38 *For whosoever shall be ashamed of me, and of my words in this adulterous and sinful generation, the Son of man also shall be ashamed of him, when he shall come in the glory of his Father with the holy Angels.
\p
\v 39 And he said to them: *Amen, I say to you, that there are some of them that stand here, who shall not taste death, till they see the kingdom of God coming in power.
